                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/4471: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-08T08:00:00+03:25"
                            >July 8, 1940—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 8—4:48 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>153. Recent statements attributed to members of the Soviet Embassy are to the
                    effect that in view of the German discoveries in Paris of documents proving
                    Allied designs on Baku and Batum the Soviet Government will probably find it
                    necessary to demand certain guarantees which will render the execution of such
                    plans impossible.</p>
                <p>This is interpreted here as foreshadowing Russian territorial claims in northern
                    Iran. See also my telegram No. 106, May 10, paragraph 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
